This article is a transcript of Executive Order 13780, issued by President Donald Trump on March 6, 2017. The order suspends the entry of foreign nationals from six countries (Iran, Libya, Somalia, Sudan, Syria, and Yemen) for a period of 90 days. It also suspends the U.S. Refugee Admissions Program for 120 days. The order states that the purpose is to protect the United States from terrorist activities by foreign nationals. The order also calls for the implementation of improved screening and vetting protocols and procedures. The article includes details on the countries affected by the order and the criteria for granting waivers to the suspension.